This is an out of the way little place around the corner from Broadway, just a few steps from the 103rd St. 1 station.  It is, however, well worth the trip.  The space is small but warm and cozy. Two of my favourites are the Tom Yum soup and Co Co shrimp.  I have taken to calling in my order as I leave the office, hopping on the subway and the order's ready by the time I arrive.  Tip:  grab a bottle from Grape Collective across the street on Broadway to pair with your dinner!

The restaurant is clean and food was brought fast. Staff are nice. They have a mix of Malaysian and Thai dishes, which should have been the first sign that it was not going to be that authentic.

I find it hard to understand why Malaysia Grill has so many positive ratings.  I think they used to be good---several years ago.  I tried it again last year (after many years in between visits)  and found the food lackluster, but did enjoy the Crispy Shrimp which I have ordered several times since.  I thought I'd give it another try now that its been about 18 months since the disappointing in-restaurant experience.  The food is actually INEDIBLE!  The Crispy Shrimp was undercooked, while I suspect that both the curry samosas and fried pork dumplings were left over from yesterday and re-fried.  If not that, they are simply way overcooked, perhaps in stale oil.  The samosa are so tough that I literally cannot eat them.  The dumplings are also overcooked producing very tough skins.  I won't be reordering again.
